37968462509048, \"rank\": 0.0661339266412632, \"text\": \"Tokyo\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Tokyo\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Tokyo\"}, {\"begin\": 333, \"end\": 345, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/2008_Summer_Olympics\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 3.7596051119188615e-16, \"text\": \"Beijing 2008\", \"types\": [\"Q1656682\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/2008_Summer_Olympics\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/2008_Summer_Olympics\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"PHOTOS: OLYMPICS.COM  PublishedJul 24, 2024, 01:30 PM  UpdatedJul 26, 2024, 12:23 PM  Olympic mascots are symbolic figures representing the host country and its culture, introduced to engage the public and promote the Olympic spirit.\", \"from\": 348, \"to\": 581, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"The first official mascot was Waldi, a dachshund, at the 1972 Munich Games.\", \"from\": 583, \"to\": 658, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 602, \"end\": 608, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mascot\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 2.8174558391608035e-48, \"text\": \"mascot\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mascot\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mascot\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"All the subsequent Olympics have featured unique mascots reflecting the host nation's heritage.\", \"from\": 659, \"to\": 754, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Here's a look at the different mascots through the years.\", \"from\": 756, \"to\": 813, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Munich 1972 - Waldi  PHOTO: OLYMPICS.COM  \\u2022 Waldi was the first official Olympic mascot.\", \"from\": 815, \"to\": 903, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 843, \"end\": 855, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Olympic_Games\", \"score\": 0.9999999891806511, \"rank\": 1.0819100304029562e-08, \"text\": \"OLYMPICS.COM\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Olympic_Games\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Olympic_Games\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"A dachshund, chosen for its qualities of resistance, tenacity and agility, which are attributes required for athletes.\", \"from\": 904, \"to\": 1022, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"\\u2022 Created by Elena Winschermann.\", \"from\": 1024, \"to\": 1056, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1037, \"end\": 1042, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Police_of_The_Wire\", \"score\": 0.9656955670877753, \"rank\": 0.03552301240961448, \"text\": \"Elena\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Police_of_The_Wire\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Police_of_The_Wire\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"\\u2022 Waldi's design was inspired by a real dachshund named Cherie von Birkenhof.\", \"from\": 1058, \"to\": 1135, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Montreal 1976 - Amik  PHOTO: OLYMPICS.COM  \\u2022 Amik is a beaver, symbolising hard work.\", \"from\": 1137, \"to\": 1222, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"It is an animal considered a national symbol of Canada.\", \"from\": 1223, \"to\": 1278, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1271, \"end\": 1277, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Canada\", \"score\": 0.9999999999990905, \"rank\": 2.405668851994726e-13, \"text\": \"Canada\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Canada\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Canada\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The word \\\"amik\\\" means \\\"beaver\\\" in the Algonquian language.\", \"from\": 1279, \"to\": 1337, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1317, \"end\": 1327, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Language\", \"score\": 0.9999985574487655, \"rank\": 1.4359826357787567e-06, \"text\": \"Algonquian\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Language\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Language\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"\\u2022 Created by Guy St-Arnaud, Yvon Laroche and Pierre-Yves Pelletier, under the leadership of Georges Huel.\", \"from\": 1339, \"to\": 1444, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1384, \"end\": 1405, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pierre-Yves_Pelletier\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Pierre-Yves Pelletier\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pierre-Yves_Pelletier\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pierre-Yves_Pelletier\"}, {\"begin\": 1439, \"end\": 1443, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Huel\", \"score\": 0.6694679025900516, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Huel\", \"types\": [\"Q4830453\", \"Q43229\", \"Q24229398\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Huel\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Huel\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"\\u2022 Amik's simple design with a red sash drew mixed reactions, leading to varying interpretations of its appearance.\", \"from\": 1446, \"to\": 1560, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Moscow 1980 - Misha  PHOTO: OLYMPICS.COM  \\u2022 Misha, a bear character associated with Russia and the Olympic Games, wears a belt with a unique design featuring the Olympic rings.\", \"from\": 1562, \"to\": 1738, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1562, \"end\": 1573, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/1980_Summer_Olympics\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.4166890798735718e-25, \"text\": \"Moscow 1980\", \"types\": [\"Q1656682\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/1980_Summer_Olympics\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/1980_Summer_Olympics\"}, {\"begin\": 1590, \"end\": 1602, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Olympic_Games\", \"score\": 0.9999999891806511, \"rank\": 1.0819100304029562e-08, \"text\": \"OLYMPICS.COM\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Olympic_Games\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Olympic_Games\"}, {\"begin\": 1606, \"end\": 1611, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Misha\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 3.923576685667692e-48, \"text\": \"Misha\", \"types\": [\"Q627603\", \"Q1107\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Misha\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Misha\"}, {\"b